node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers Just helped a young military man set up a tax free retirement plan. He's 26. $600 a month. If he never increases the monthly amount, at age 65 he'll have $1,259,207. And, tax-free income of....wait for it... $99,500 a year. For LIFE.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers When he retires from the military at 38, he'll also get about $2,500 a month, and go into corporate or government service. Somewhere in there, we'll probably add another one of these accounts, get him investing up to the match in his 401k, and invest in some real estate.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers I've seen a lot of notes about inflation. Some intelligent, some less so. But, it's a fair point: What WILL $99,500 a year be worth in 39 years? First off, it's tax-free, so whatever rate taxes are at, it's worth that much more.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers Right now, between that and his military pension, he would be in the 22% bracket. And 6% for the state of CA So, on that money, if it WASN'T tax free, he would have to make $138,194 just to net the $99,500 However, at 3% inflation THAT amount is really only worth about $43,635'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers But, the advantage that THIS account has is that he has access to the money before he's 59 1/2. So, he can use the money for: -a house down payment; -a wedding; -Investments; -Even his own kids's education. His other accounts will force him to pay tax and penalties.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers So, it's a fair point. On the other hand... 1.1 1. DELIBERATELY used a much more conservative interest rate than what that plan has historically earned so the real numbers are likely to be (somewhat) higher. 2. It's just ONE piece of his financial plan.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers 3. We're also assuming that he never increases his $600/month contributions.....but, his salary and income WILL increase over the next 39 years. So, his contributions to this and other accounts will likely increase as well, but I didn't show that.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers 4. However, for those of you saying that putting $273,600 into an account and getting an income stream of $99,500 a year for the rest of his life is BAD??! He puts in that amount, If he lives to 86, he pulls out $2,189,000 tax free. And still has $1,079,000 in cash.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers 5. And for those of you that are saying: 'WeLl, hE SHoULd Day TraDe AnD mAkE MOrE' Or put it all in stocks. Maybe he will later. Nothing wrong with that either. But saying he's 'guaranteed' to make a 22% return so he shouldn't do this? Yeah. No.'.

Photo shared by The #1 Investment Page📈 on September 11, 2021 tagging @ronocaruthers. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ron Caruthers @roncaruthers A couple more notes on this I used a properly structured Index Universal Life Insurance. Key words: Properly structured. So it literally has the least amount of death benefit possible. We're also contributing to a Roth IRA and he has a TSP.'.
